For your dedicated Non-Cycling Mobility Focus on Day 17 (Friday, June 5, 2026), the goal is to open up the exact muscle groups that get locked into a tight, compressed position during long hours of cycling: the glutes, lower back, and hip flexors.
​Because I am a text-based AI, I cannot directly embed playable video boxes here, but I have selected the best, highly-rated YouTube mobility routines specifically tailored for cyclists. These routines are gentle, require zero equipment, and focus purely on functional decompression to get you ready for your trip.
​Choose one or mix these routines on your mobility day:
​1. The Full-Body Cyclist Reset (Deep Release)
​The Routine: Yoga for Cyclists - Restorative Recovery Routine by Yoga With Adriene
​Why it works: This is a classic 25-minute, zero-intensity session that focuses entirely on elongating the spine, stretching out the lower back, and breathing into tight hip complexes. It is perfect for a rest phase because it adds absolutely zero muscular fatigue.
​2. Targeted Hip Flexor & Glute Opening (Short & Sharp)
​The Routine: 15-Minute Flexibility Routine for Cyclists by Global Cycling Network (GCN)
​Why it works: GCN is the gold standard for cycling-specific biomechanics. This quick routine targets the deep psoas and hip flexor muscles that get shortened during the pedal stroke, while incorporating dynamic movements to unlock stiff lower back tissues.
​3. Lower Back Decompression
​The Routine: 10-Minute Lower Back Flexibility and Mobility for Riders by Tom Merrick
​Why it works: If you experience any tight "aching" sensations in your lower spine after long indoor trainer block sessions, this quick sequence focuses entirely on decompression, pelvic tilts, and thoracic rotation to build a supple trunk.
​💡 Execution Tips for Day 17:
​Never stretch to the point of pain: On a pure recovery day, aim for a gentle "7 out of 10" sensation on the stretch intensity scale. You are trying to signal your nervous system to relax and let go of tension, not tear the muscle tissue.
​Warm tissues stretch better: Try to do these routines in a warm room, or right after a warm shower/bath when your joints and muscles are naturally more compliant!
